[+ nsdap_leader +] seeks a private conversation with Hindenburg’s son, while Göring speaks separately with Meissner. [+ nsdap_leader +]’s effort to sway the reluctant Oskar to back his appointment as presidential chancellor fails—prompting Goebbels to describe Oskar as “the personification of stupidity.” In contrast, Göring, now serving as [+ nsdap_leader +]’s spokesman, takes a more measured approach. Leveraging his reputation as a respected war hero and his skilled social ability, he assures Meissner that the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> would demand only a single cabinet post, with the President retaining control over the crucial Foreign and Defense Ministries.

By the end of the day’s talks, consensus forms around a single point: Schleicher must go. An unspoken deal takes shape—Papen signals his willingness to accept the vice-chancellorship under [+ nsdap_chancellor +], and [+ nsdap_leader +], through Göring, makes it clear he is ready to offer major concessions in a cabinet led by him.